[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] Gradient descent works in spaces of any number of dimensions, even in infinite-dimensional ones.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] In the latter case, the search space is typically a function space, and one calculates the Fréchet derivative of the functional to be minimized to determine the descent direction.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] That gradient descent works in any number of dimensions (finite number at least) can be seen as a consequence of the Cauchy–Schwarz inequality, i.e. the magnitude of the inner (dot) product of two vectors of any dimension is maximized when they are colinear.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] In the case of gradient descent, that would be when the vector of independent variable adjustments is proportional to the gradient vector of partial derivatives.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] The gradient descent can take many iterations to compute a local minimum with a required accuracy, if the curvature in different directions is very different for the given function.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] For such functions, preconditioning, which changes the geometry of the space to shape the function level sets like concentric circles, cures the slow convergence.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] Constructing and applying preconditioning can be computationally expensive, however.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] The gradient descent can be modified via momentums (Nesterov, Polyak, and Frank–Wolfe) and heavy-ball parameters (exponential moving averages and positive-negative momentum).
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] The main examples of such optimizers are Adam, DiffGrad, Yogi, AdaBelief, etc.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] Methods based on Newton's method and inversion of the Hessian using conjugate gradient techniques can be better alternatives.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] Generally, such methods converge in fewer iterations, but the cost of each iteration is higher.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] While it is sometimes possible to substitute gradient descent for a local search algorithm, gradient descent is not in the same family: although it is an iterative method for local optimization, it relies on an objective function's gradient rather than an explicit exploration of a solution space.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] Gradient descent can be viewed as applying Euler's method for solving ordinary differential equations $x'(t)=-\nabla f(x(t))$ to a gradient flow.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] In turn, this equation may be derived as an optimal controller for the control system $x'(t)=u(t)$ with $u(t)$ given in feedback form $u(t)=-\nabla f(x(t))$ .
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] Gradient descent can converge to a local minimum and slow down in a neighborhood of a saddle point.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] Even for unconstrained quadratic minimization, gradient descent develops a zig–zag pattern of subsequent iterates as iterations progress, resulting in slow convergence.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] Multiple modifications of gradient descent have been proposed to address these deficiencies.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] Yurii Nesterov has proposed a simple modification that enables faster convergence for convex problems and has been since further generalized.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] For unconstrained smooth problems, the method is called the fast gradient method (FGM) or the accelerated gradient method (AGM).
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] Specifically, if the differentiable function f is convex and $\nabla f$ is Lipschitz, and it is not assumed that f is strongly convex, then the error in the objective value generated at each step k by the gradient descent method will be bounded by ${\textstyle {\mathcal {O}}\left({k^{-1}}\right)}$ .
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] Using the Nesterov acceleration technique, the error decreases at ${\textstyle {\mathcal {O}}\left({k^{-2}}\right)}$ .
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] It is known that the rate ${\mathcal {O}}\left({k^{-2}}\right)$ for the decrease of the cost function is optimal for first-order optimization methods.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] Nevertheless, there is the opportunity to improve the algorithm by reducing the constant factor.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] The optimized gradient method (OGM) reduces that constant by a factor of two and is an optimal first-order method for large-scale problems.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] For constrained or non-smooth problems, Nesterov's FGM is called the fast proximal gradient method (FPGM), an acceleration of the proximal gradient method.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] Gradient descent with momentum remembers the solution update at each iteration, and determines the next update as a linear combination of the gradient and the previous update.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] For unconstrained quadratic minimization, a theoretical convergence rate bound of the heavy ball method is asymptotically the same as that for the optimal conjugate gradient method.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] This technique is used in stochastic gradient descent and as an extension to the backpropagation algorithms used to train artificial neural networks.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] In the direction of updating, stochastic gradient descent adds a stochastic property.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] The weights can be used to calculate the derivatives.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] Gradient descent can be extended to handle constraints by including a projection onto the set of constraints.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] This method is only feasible when the projection is efficiently computable on a computer.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] Under suitable assumptions, this method converges.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] This method is a specific case of the forward–backward algorithm for monotone inclusions (which includes convex programming and variational inequalities).
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] Gradient descent is a special case of mirror descent using the squared Euclidean distance as the given Bregman divergence.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] The properties of gradient descent depend on the properties of the objective function and the variant of gradient descent used (for example, if a line search step is used).
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] The assumptions made affect the convergence rate, and other properties, that can be proven for gradient descent.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] For example, if the objective is assumed to be strongly convex and lipschitz smooth, then gradient descent converges linearly with a fixed step size.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/gradient-descent] Looser assumptions lead to either weaker convergence guarantees or require a more sophisticated step size selection.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/learning-rate] In machine learning and statistics, the **learning rate** is a tuning parameter in an optimization algorithm that determines the step size at each iteration while moving toward a minimum of a loss function.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/learning-rate] Since it influences to what extent newly acquired information overrides old information, it metaphorically represents the speed at which a machine learning model "learns".
[src:gradient-descent-variants/learning-rate] In the adaptive control literature, the learning rate is commonly referred to as **gain**.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/learning-rate] In setting a learning rate, there is a trade-off between the rate of convergence and overshooting.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/learning-rate] While the descent direction is usually determined from the gradient of the loss function, the learning rate determines how big a step is taken in that direction.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/learning-rate] Too high a learning rate will make the learning jump over minima, but too low a learning rate will either take too long to converge or get stuck in an undesirable local minimum.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/learning-rate] In order to achieve faster convergence, prevent oscillations and getting stuck in undesirable local minima the learning rate is often varied during training either in accordance to a learning rate schedule or by using an adaptive learning rate.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/learning-rate] The learning rate and its adjustments may also differ per parameter, in which case it is a diagonal matrix that can be interpreted as an approximation to the inverse of the Hessian matrix in Newton's method.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/learning-rate] The learning rate is related to the step length determined by inexact line search in quasi-Newton methods and related optimization algorithms.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/learning-rate] Initial rate can be left as system default or can be selected using a range of techniques.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/learning-rate] A learning rate schedule changes the learning rate during learning and is most often changed between epochs/iterations.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/learning-rate] This is mainly done with two parameters: **decay** and **momentum**.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/learning-rate] There are many different learning rate schedules but the most common are **time-based, step-based** and **exponential**.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/learning-rate] where $\eta$ is the learning rate, $\eta _{0}$ is the original learning rate, d is a decay parameter and n is the iteration step.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/learning-rate] The *floor* function ( $\lfloor \dots \rfloor$ ) here drops the value of its input to 0 for all values smaller than 1.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/learning-rate] The issue with learning rate schedules is that they all depend on hyperparameters that must be manually chosen for each given learning session and may vary greatly depending on the problem at hand or the model used.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/learning-rate] To combat this, there are many different types of adaptive gradient descent algorithms such as Adagrad, Adadelta, RMSprop, and Adam which are generally built into deep learning libraries such as Keras.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] The basic idea behind stochastic approximation can be traced back to the Robbins–Monro algorithm of the 1950s.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] Today, stochastic gradient descent has become an important optimization method in machine learning.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] Both statistical estimation and machine learning consider the problem of minimizing an objective function that has the form of a sum: $Q(w)={\frac {1}{n}}\sum _{i=1}^{n}Q_{i}(w),$ where the parameter w that minimizes $Q(w)$ is to be estimated.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] Each summand function $Q_{i}$ is typically associated with the i -th observation in the data set (used for training).
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] In classical statistics, sum-minimization problems arise in least squares and in maximum-likelihood estimation (for independent observations).
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] The general class of estimators that arise as minimizers of sums are called M-estimators.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] However, in statistics, it has been long recognized that requiring even local minimization is too restrictive for some problems of maximum-likelihood estimation.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] Therefore, contemporary statistical theorists often consider stationary points of the likelihood function (or zeros of its derivative, the score function, and other estimating equations).
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] The sum-minimization problem also arises for empirical risk minimization.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] There, $Q_{i}(w)$ is the value of the loss function at i -th example, and $Q(w)$ is the empirical risk.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] In many cases, the summand functions have a simple form that enables inexpensive evaluations of the sum-function and the sum gradient.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] For example, in statistics, one-parameter exponential families allow economical function-evaluations and gradient-evaluations.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] However, in other cases, evaluating the sum-gradient may require expensive evaluations of the gradients from all summand functions.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] When the training set is enormous and no simple formulas exist, evaluating the sums of gradients becomes very expensive, because evaluating the gradient requires evaluating all the summand functions' gradients.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] To economize on the computational cost at every iteration, stochastic gradient descent samples a subset of summand functions at every step.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] This is very effective in the case of large-scale machine learning problems.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] In stochastic (or "on-line") gradient descent, the true gradient of $Q(w)$ is approximated by a gradient at a single sample: $w:=w-\eta \,\nabla Q_{i}(w).$ As the algorithm sweeps through the training set, it performs the above update for each training sample.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] Several passes can be made over the training set until the algorithm converges.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] If this is done, the data can be shuffled for each pass to prevent cycles.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] Typical implementations may use an adaptive learning rate so that the algorithm converges.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] A compromise between computing the true gradient and the gradient at a single sample is to compute the gradient against more than one training sample (called a "mini-batch") at each step.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] This can perform significantly better than "true" stochastic gradient descent described, because the code can make use of vectorization libraries rather than computing each step separately as was first shown in where it was called "the bunch-mode back-propagation algorithm".
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] It may also result in smoother convergence, as the gradient computed at each step is averaged over more training samples.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] The convergence of stochastic gradient descent has been analyzed using the theories of convex minimization and of stochastic approximation.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] This is in fact a consequence of the Robbins–Siegmund theorem.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] This is the key difference between stochastic gradient descent and batched gradient descent.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] In general, given a linear regression ${\hat {y}}=\sum _{k\in 1:m}w_{k}x_{k}$ problem, stochastic gradient descent behaves differently when $m<n$ (underparameterized) and $m\geq n$ (overparameterized).
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] In the overparameterized case, stochastic gradient descent converges to $\arg \min _{w:w^{T}x_{k}=y_{k}\forall k\in 1:n}\|w-w_{0}\|$ .
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] That is, SGD converges to the interpolation solution with minimum distance from the starting $w_{0}$ .
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] This is true even when the learning rate remains constant.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] In the underparameterized case, SGD does not converge if learning rate remains constant.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] In 1951, Herbert Robbins and Sutton Monro introduced the earliest stochastic approximation methods, preceding stochastic gradient descent.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] Building on this work one year later, Jack Kiefer and Jacob Wolfowitz published an optimization algorithm very close to stochastic gradient descent, using central differences as an approximation of the gradient.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] Later in the 1950s, Frank Rosenblatt used SGD to optimize his perceptron model, demonstrating the first applicability of stochastic gradient descent to neural networks.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] Backpropagation was first described in 1986, with stochastic gradient descent being used to efficiently optimize parameters across neural networks with multiple hidden layers.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] Soon after, another improvement was developed: mini-batch gradient descent, where small batches of data are substituted for single samples.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] In 1997, the practical performance benefits from vectorization achievable with such small batches were first explored, paving the way for efficient optimization in machine learning.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] As of 2023, this mini-batch approach remains the norm for training neural networks, balancing the benefits of stochastic gradient descent with gradient descent.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] By the 1980s, momentum had already been introduced, and was added to SGD optimization techniques in 1986.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] However, these optimization techniques assumed constant hyperparameters, i.e. a fixed learning rate and momentum parameter.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] In the 2010s, adaptive approaches to applying SGD with a per-parameter learning rate were introduced with AdaGrad (for "Adaptive Gradient") in 2011 and RMSprop (for "Root Mean Square Propagation") in 2012.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] In 2014, Adam (for "Adaptive Moment Estimation") was published, applying the adaptive approaches of RMSprop to momentum; many improvements and branches of Adam were then developed such as Adadelta, Adagrad, AdamW, and Adamax.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] Within machine learning, approaches to optimization in 2023 are dominated by Adam-derived optimizers, TensorFlow and PyTorch, by far the most popular machine learning libraries, as of 2023 largely only include Adam-derived optimizers, as well as predecessors to Adam such as RMSprop and classic SGD.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] PyTorch also partially supports limited-memory BFGS, a line-search method, but only for single-device setups without parameter groups.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] Stochastic gradient descent is a popular algorithm for training a wide range of models in machine learning, including (linear) support vector machines, logistic regression (see, e.g., Vowpal Wabbit) and graphical models.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] When combined with the backpropagation algorithm, it is the *de facto* standard algorithm for training artificial neural networks.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] Its use has been also reported in the Geophysics community, specifically to applications of Full Waveform Inversion (FWI).
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] Stochastic gradient descent competes with the L-BFGS algorithm, which is also widely used.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] Stochastic gradient descent has been used since at least 1960 for training linear regression models, originally under the name ADALINE.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] Another stochastic gradient descent algorithm is the least mean squares (LMS) adaptive filter.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] Many improvements on the basic stochastic gradient descent algorithm have been proposed and used.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] In particular, in machine learning, the need to set a learning rate (step size) has been recognized as problematic.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] Setting this parameter too high can cause the algorithm to diverge; setting it too low makes it slow to converge.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] A conceptually simple extension of stochastic gradient descent makes the learning rate a decreasing function ηt of the iteration number t, giving a *learning rate schedule*, so that the first iterations cause large changes in the parameters, while the later ones do only fine-tuning.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] Such schedules have been known since the work of MacQueen on k-means clustering.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] Practical guidance on choosing the step size in several variants of SGD is given by Spall.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] As mentioned earlier, classical stochastic gradient descent is generally sensitive to learning rate η.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] Fast convergence requires large learning rates but this may induce numerical instability.
