[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] The concept of storing the historical gradient as sum of squares is borrowed from Adagrad, but "forgetting" is introduced to solve Adagrad's diminishing learning rates in non-convex problems by gradually decreasing the influence of old data.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] RMSProp has shown good adaptation of learning rate in different applications.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] RMSProp can be seen as a generalization of Rprop and is capable to work with mini-batches as well opposed to only full-batches.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] 0.999) are the forgetting factors for gradients and second moments of gradients, respectively.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] Squaring and square-rooting is done element-wise.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] As the exponential moving averages of the gradient $m_{w}^{(t)}$ and the squared gradient $v_{w}^{(t)}$ are initialized with a vector of 0's, there would be a bias towards zero in the first training iterations.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] The initial proof establishing the convergence of Adam was incomplete, and subsequent analysis has revealed that Adam does not converge for all convex objectives.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] Despite this, *Adam* continues to be used due to its strong performance in practice.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] The popularity of *Adam* inspired many variants and enhancements.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] Even though sign-based optimization goes back to the aforementioned *Rprop*, in 2018 researchers tried to simplify Adam by removing the magnitude of the stochastic gradient from being taken into account and only considering its sign.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] This results in a significantly lower communication cost of transferring gradients from workers to the parameter server.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] In this sense, it serves to better compress the gradient information, while having comparable convergence to standard SGD.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] Backtracking line search is another variant of gradient descent.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] All of the below are sourced from the mentioned link.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] It is based on a condition known as the Armijo–Goldstein condition.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] Both methods allow learning rates to change at each iteration; however, the manner of the change is different.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] Backtracking line search uses function evaluations to check Armijo's condition, and in principle the loop in the algorithm for determining the learning rates can be long and unknown in advance.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] Adaptive SGD does not need a loop in determining learning rates.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] On the other hand, adaptive SGD does not guarantee the "descent property" – which Backtracking line search enjoys – which is that $f(x_{n+1})\leq f(x_{n})$ for all n.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] If the gradient of the cost function is globally Lipschitz continuous, with Lipschitz constant L, and learning rate is chosen of the order 1/L, then the standard version of SGD is a special case of backtracking line search.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] A stochastic analogue of the standard (deterministic) Newton–Raphson algorithm (a "second-order" method) provides an asymptotically optimal or near-optimal form of iterative optimization in the setting of stochastic approximation.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] A method that uses direct measurements of the Hessian matrices of the summands in the empirical risk function was developed by Byrd, Hansen, Nocedal, and Singer.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] However, directly determining the required Hessian matrices for optimization may not be possible in practice.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] Practical and theoretically sound methods for second-order versions of SGD that do not require direct Hessian information are given by Spall and others.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] (A less efficient method based on finite differences, instead of simultaneous perturbations, is given by Ruppert.) Another approach to the approximation Hessian matrix is replacing it with the Fisher information matrix, which transforms usual gradient to natural.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] These methods not requiring direct Hessian information are based on either values of the summands in the above empirical risk function or values of the gradients of the summands (i.e., the SGD inputs).
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] In particular, second-order optimality is asymptotically achievable without direct calculation of the Hessian matrices of the summands in the empirical risk function.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] This approximation is only valid on a finite time-horizon in the following sense: assume that all the coefficients ${\textstyle Q_{i}}$ are sufficiently smooth.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] Let ${\textstyle T>0}$ and ${\textstyle g:\mathbb {R} ^{d}\to \mathbb {R} }$ be a sufficiently smooth test function.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] where ${\textstyle \mathbb {E} }$ denotes taking the expectation with respect to the random choice of indices in the stochastic gradient descent scheme.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] Since this approximation does not capture the random fluctuations around the mean behavior of stochastic gradient descent solutions to stochastic differential equations (SDEs) have been proposed as limiting objects.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] However this SDE only approximates the one-point motion of stochastic gradient descent.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/stochastic-gradient-descent] For an approximation of the stochastic flow one has to consider SDEs with infinite-dimensional noise.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/subgradient-method] Subgradient methods are slower than Newton's method when applied to minimize twice continuously differentiable convex functions.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/subgradient-method] However, Newton's method fails to converge on problems that have non-differentiable kinks.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/subgradient-method] In recent years, some interior-point methods have been suggested for convex minimization problems, but subgradient projection methods and related bundle methods of descent remain competitive.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/subgradient-method] For convex minimization problems with very large number of dimensions, subgradient-projection methods are suitable, because they require little storage.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/subgradient-method] Subgradient projection methods are often applied to large-scale problems with decomposition techniques.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/subgradient-method] Such decomposition methods often allow a simple distributed method for a problem.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/subgradient-method] Many different types of step-size rules are used by subgradient methods.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/subgradient-method] For all five rules, the step-sizes are determined "off-line", before the method is iterated; the step-sizes do not depend on preceding iterations.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/subgradient-method] An extensive discussion of stepsize rules for subgradient methods, including incremental versions, is given in the books by Bertsekas and by Bertsekas, Nedic, and Ozdaglar.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/subgradient-method] These classical subgradient methods have poor performance and are no longer recommended for general use.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/subgradient-method] However, they are still used widely in specialized applications because they are simple and they can be easily adapted to take advantage of the special structure of the problem at hand.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/subgradient-method] During the 1970s, Claude Lemaréchal and Phil Wolfe proposed "bundle methods" of descent for problems of convex minimization.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/subgradient-method] The meaning of the term "bundle methods" has changed significantly since that time.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/subgradient-method] Modern versions and full convergence analysis were provided by Kiwiel.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/subgradient-method] Contemporary bundle-methods often use "level control" rules for choosing step-sizes, developing techniques from the "subgradient-projection" method of Boris T.
[src:gradient-descent-variants/subgradient-method] However, there are problems on which bundle methods offer little advantage over subgradient-projection methods.
